[2026-07-09 14:30:38] вЖТ 22501535027310: What you and I discussed in the car is this:

* Product investments can be made on a spectrum: from *founder gut* to *market research validated* (with *seller/customer/field signaled* somewhere in between)
* вБ†Founder Gut type decisions are cheap to make, Market Research Validated ones are expensive.
* вБ†There are costs to getting the decision wrong: 
* вБ†1. Opportunity cost of not building something else that is known to be needed
* вБ†2. GTM orgвАЩs investment in taking the product to market
* вБ†3. Culture impact of not winning when product doesnвАЩt find PMF
* вБ†In our situation, I suspect (not certain, but suspect) that we donвАЩt have cost #1 because every вАЬgoodвАЭ idea that we all believe is worthwhile is being funded and built.  For example, if we didnвАЩt build any W365/Intune functionality, what would be build instead?  I donвАЩt think anyone knows.  We havenвАЩt said вАЬnoвАЭ to some other high potential product in favor of W365/Intune and are now regretting doing it.  So my point is that the true cost of вАЬmoving fastвАЭ and launching products based on вАЬfounder gutвАЭ validation side of the spectrum is not costing us that much.  On the contrary, it could be saving us time/money by not going through formal market research to validate every possible idea before building it.
* вБ†If the above is true, the question of where should we be investing on the product side comes in.  We can invest in enhancing AVD functionality, which not only are we already doing, but there is probably not much more we need to invest to win business.  We can also invest in promising new product ideas and concepts, like weвАЩre doing with W365, Intune, etc.
* вБ†The true cost shifts to GTM.  Taking a product to market and not finding PMF sucks.  GTM team should be finding the shortest path to ARR.  This means favoring PMF-validated products over new ones, as long as the TAM hasnвАЩt been exhausted.
* вБ†Selling AVD used to be easy.  Microsoft would pull us in, we didnвАЩt have competition, there was no W365 to position against, customers who really needed us had no options.  Win rates were very high.
* вБ†It became much harder.  AVD isnвАЩt growing as fast, W365 is the hero motion, many customers already have Nerdio, Microsoft isnвАЩt excited about us any longer, this all leads to shrinking win rates.  
* вБ†I suspect the sales team is expecting an вАЬeasy saleвАЭ by picking up вАЬlow hanging fruitвАЭ customers, which was the case with AVD for a while and is no longer the case.  They have the climb the tree much higher.  Therefore, they are looking to product to hand them another magic product that will make selling as easy as AVD used to be.  IвАЩd love to do that and we have been trying, but no luck so far.
* вБ†So what does that practically mean?  I think LarryвАЩs framework is the right way to look at it.  Define all the motions, score them on a dimension like Win Rate, compare them to each other and decide where to put the bets.  To me it looks like AVD should be getting disproportionate amount of investment on GTM, product should continue building the products that we have customer-validated to be needed and Sales should be experimenting and perfecting selling those products while feeding Product with the intel they need to make them even better.

Do you agree with the above?
